28036.title: Portrait of a Man
28036.credit_line: The Orville A. and Elma D. Wilkinson Fund
28036.provenance: The artist;...Mr. and Mrs. Paul Barton of Indianapolis circa 1960; IMA 1975

extended_text.content:
James Peale's likeness of Revolutionary War officer Thomas Humphrey Cushing is typical of his best technique. Peale passed his skills on to his daughter Anna whose portrait is similar to her father's natural flesh tones and firm drawing style.

Miniature portraits have been used as mementos since ancient times.

22394.title: Indian Pueblos
22394.credit_line: Gift of the Harrison Eiteljorg Gallery of Western Art

extended_text.content:
Fechin developed a dramatic style consisting of vigorous brush strokes and vivid colors.

The artist loved the somber forests near his home in Russia and found their equivalent in the New Mexico Plateau, where he settled in 1927.

The Pueblo Indians rekindled Fechin's interest in the culture and heritage of native peoples.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label
